The tadpole is not as large as that of Amareucium, but shows
an interesting feature not present in that form. 'Just under the
adhesive papillae are a group of accessory hearts, folded up like
the petals of a rosebud. ln metamorphosis, they unfold and spread

lhe animal is clearer and larger, and usually so oriented
that the observer looks directly into the atrial and eral siphons.
The large pharynx shows one row of stigmata around it. The endostyl
lies on the under side of the pharynx and thus appears as a rod
under the mouth.
The stomach ordinarily appears as a yellow body under the
atrial opening. The intestine, after turning to one side from the
stomach, returns to open near the atrium. The pulsating heart and
its vessels are of particular interest, especially the flow of
blood around the mouth and pharynx.
